ion toward approval in recent years\n- The 94-day window is short for a regulatory breakthrough in India's bureaucratic system\n- If approval were imminent, we'd typically see official announcements or regulatory filings first\n- The fact this question is being refreshed at 12% suggests no major developments have shifted the outlook\n\n**(g) How my view has changed since original forecast:**\nThe 12% baseline appears well-calibrated for this question. The main considerations:\n- 3 months is a relatively tight timeframe for India regulatory approval\n- India has historically been slow on telecom liberalization decisions\n- The political/bureaucratic dynamics haven't visibly shifted to create urgency\n- Starlink expansion to 70 countries shows capability, but India remains uniquely difficult\n\nI would not significantly move away from the 12% estimate. Perhaps marginal adjustment to 10-14% range, but the original assessment appears sound.\n\n**(h) Community prediction and divergence:**\nThe original 12% appears to be a well-reasoned community estimate. Without evidence of recent regulatory breakthroughs or policy shifts toward approval in India, there's no strong reason to diverge materially from this.\n\nThe key consideration is whether \"show on website\" might happen before formal approval (unlikely) versus requiring actual regulatory sign-off (what typically happens).\n\n**Probability: 12%**\n\nThis reflects: (a) the inherent difficulty of India's regulatory process, (b) the relatively short 94-day timeframe, (c) lack of clear signals of imminent approval, and (d) the historical pattern of delays in this specific case. While not impossible (India could announce approval quickly if political will materializes), base rates and the status quo strongly favor continued non-availability.",
