e for government regulatory approval in India\n- No evidence of imminent government decision in the next 94 days\n- India's Department of Telecommunications typically moves slowly\n- The previous 4% forecast likely reflected these barriers\n\n(g) How your view has changed (or not) since the original forecast\nThe 4% forecast from before appears well-calibrated. The factors that made it unlikely then remain true now:\n- Same regulatory barriers exist\n- Same timeline constraints apply\n- No new public announcements suggest imminent approval\n- If anything, the passage of time with no approval is weak evidence of continued resistance\n\n(h) If community prediction exists and differs >10%, explain why you diverge\nNo current community prediction data provided, but the 4% prior appears reasonable and defensible.\n\n---\n\n**Analysis:**\n\nThe key question is whether India's government would approve and Starlink would operationalize within 94 days. This requires:\n1. Government approval (highly uncertain, no recent public signals of imminent decision)\n2. Infrastructure/compliance completion (possible if already partially done)\n3. Website update (trivial once approved)\n\nThe bottleneck is clearly government approval. Indian regulatory timelines are notoriously slow, and approving a major foreign satellite operator faces national security, economic protectionism, and bureaucratic inertia obstacles.\n\nWhile Musk's engagement with India shows some optimism about eventual entry, the 3-month window is extremely compressed for such a major regulatory decision. Historical precedent suggests government approvals in India's telecom/space sector take 6+ months minimum after serious negotiations.\n\nThe previous 4% estimate appropriately captured:\n- Low base probability of any major regulatory reversal in 3 months\n- The ongoing nature of negotiations without resolution\n- Institutional inertia in Indian government\n\nThere is no evidence that the timeline has accelerated or that approval is imminent. Slight upward adjustment warranted only if credible news emerged of imminent approval, which appears absent.\n\n**Probability: 6%**\n\n(Slight upward movement from 4% to 6% acknowledging: (1) possibility of unexpected rapid government decision, (2) existing engagement between Musk and Indian officials suggesting some path forward, (3) general uncertainty in forecasting. However, remaining in low single digits as base rates and current evidence strongly suggest non-approval in this timeframe.)",
